5) Capability Gating (plan/module enforcement)

Capabilities are derived from tenant plan + add-ons.

5.1 Capabilities (current)
	•	CAP_SITE (effectively always enabled for all plans)
	•	CAP_STORE (Mid / Pro)
	•	CAP_SCHEDULING (Pro)

5.2 Action → Capability rules (current)
	•	Site:
	•	SITE_EDIT → CAP_SITE
	•	SITE_PUBLISH → CAP_SITE
	•	Store:
	•	PRODUCT_MANAGE, CATEGORY_MANAGE, PRICING_MANAGE, PRODUCT_MEDIA_MANAGE → CAP_STORE
	•	Orders/Selling:
	•	ORDER_VIEW, ORDER_MANAGE, REFUND_MANAGE, SALE_CREATE → CAP_STORE
	•	Scheduling:
	•	SERVICE_MANAGE, BOOKING_MANAGE → CAP_SCHEDULING
	•	Admin settings:
	•	capability gating optional; role gating is primary (admin-only)

Example: STAFF might have SERVICE_MANAGE, but if the tenant is Mid (no scheduling), policy denies due to missing CAP_SCHEDULING.

⸻

6) Enforcement Architecture

6.1 Required checks for every protected request

Policy must enforce in this order:
	1.	Tenant scope match
	•	requested {tenantId} must match token tenant (or membership selection if multi-tenant)
	2.	Membership status must be ACTIVE (hard deny otherwise)
	3.	Role allows action
	4.	Tenant has required capability

6.2 Where enforcement happens
	•	Service layer calls policy.require(...) (recommended)
	•	Controllers remain thin
	•	Optional: you can also use @PreAuthorize but it must delegate to policy; no inline role checks.

⸻

7) Multi-tenant Users (token scoping)
	•	A user can have memberships in multiple tenants.
	•	Login may require tenant selection.
	•	Access token contains one tenantId, and authorization is evaluated only for that tenant.

This avoids accidental cross-tenant operations.

⸻

8) Membership lifecycle and immediate lockout

Membership status values:
	•	INVITED
	•	ACTIVE
	•	DISABLED

Rule (locked): If membership becomes DISABLED, user loses access immediately.
	•	Policy must check membership status on each request (from DB/cache).

⸻

9) Refresh token rotation & security behaviors that interact with authorization

While this is primarily auth/session, it impacts access control safety.
	•	Access TTL: 15 minutes
	•	Refresh TTL: 14 hours
	•	Refresh rotation: enabled
	•	No expiry warnings; user re-logins when refresh expires.

Locked edge-case rules
	1.	Membership disabled mid-session → access denied immediately (policy check)
	2.	Refresh token reuse after rotation → treat as theft:
	•	revoke all refresh tokens for {userId, tenantId}
	•	clear cookie
	•	return 401

